So when the doctor, when I awakened and the doctors came in and they asked you all those questions and they said, what will you do?
I said, I fell down the stairs.
And, uh, you know, and I don't know who that upperclassman was, but I always thought that I did the right thing because nobody got in trouble.
And it was my, it was my mistake for hitting my head on a radiator.
Um,
Yeah, okay.
I didn't talk about President Williams, but I got to meet him at Clemson.
Oh, yes, yes.
When I was an ROTC instructor and going to graduate school at night at Clemson, I was playing handball with the athletic director at Clemson in the summer before, I guess it was the summer of 72.
saw where the Aggies were going to come to Clemson University for the first time ever.
And Clemson was still a high school football team.
They were a powerhouse of a basketball program, but their football program was sophomoreish.
And the Aggies, by 72, had a heck of a program.
And so, man, the Aggies were coming to Clemson.
And we were on the East Coast there, so I told athletic director, if you can get me 50 tickets that I can buy together on the 50-yard line, I'll get 50 Aggies there.
When it was all said and done, we had 1,500.
The band didn't come, but the Rioliers came and Dr. Williams came because he had been from Clemson.
And all of a sudden, I think he figured out that he's got 1,500 Aggies coming from Washington, D.C. to Florida and all the Carolinas and Georgia.
And he can go back to his old school and he can kill...
several birds with one stone.
So he came and we had a big barbecue the night before.
And then we had the, you know, all the activities, had yellow practice before the game.
And we beat Clemson so bad it was, matter of fact, I was kind of proud of the Aggies.
They played the second half, they played their third, fourth, and fifth teams the whole, the first, second, third team didn't play the second half.
And they beat them like 40 or 50 to nothing.
It was terrible.

but but uh you know they was done with class i mean they could have beat them 100 to nothing at the rate they were going um but i got to meet dr williams one time and it was very personal i mean i was the guy in charge of the setting up this program and everything and so you know i was escorting him around and and i'd you know i knew the president of clemson at the time i'd gotten to know him a little bit and i knew a lot of leadership in the athletic department so it was kind of a special weekend for me and i thought
You know, and I hadn't, he was, you know, the General's successor, and I felt pretty good after meeting him that he could handle, you know, the General Rutter legacy.
You know, I was impressed with his credentials.
Yeah, balanced life.
Yeah, I got that point.
Yeah, sir, I pretty well, I think I hit all the points on your notes.
Then the last question.
Yes, sir.
What feelings do you carry in your heart for Texas A&M now?
At 56, and I just turned 56 last month, and now I'm back here, and I'm
interacting again with old friends.
Oh, I forgot to talk about Buck Wires, but Buck was a good friend of mine.
I mean, and I dated his daughter.
It was one of the few ladies that I would date, and I don't think we were ever going to be in love, but we were good friends.
And then I got to know Buck through his daughter, and he was special.
But I think being back and everything here, I went back to Houston after being gone for 37, 38 years, and I was not at home.
I stayed there three months.
I was in my old stomping grounds.
That's where we got our apartment.
And Jeannie and I were just not comfortable.
We came up here and we moved to College Station.
And it has been coming home.
And so in my heart, I've lived all over the world.
I've been to 63 countries at least once, and I've been to several of them a dozen times.
And I come back to Texas A&M, and I've come back home.
And that's a feeling.
that you can only get if you've been all around the world for most of your adult life and done all the things I've done.
And it's a very comforting feeling.
I've gotten to know Dr. Bowen, and I'm so inspired from all the things he's had to do and his handling of the bonfire.
I thought it was such world-class handling of such a traumatic event.
When you send your kids to the military, you know there's a chance they'll die in combat, but when you send them to college, you don't think they're going to die.
And I've been very impressed with how he and the leadership
has handled something that I thought was, you know, one of the great tragedies of all universities.

So, no, it's hard to describe, and I don't do an adequate job of articulating really personal feelings, but it is, I think it capsulates it when I say, when we came back to A&M to live, and Jeannie says, the next move is to the cemetery.
This is our 27th home, and we feel like we're at home.
We're with friends.
We're in an unbelievable comfort zone here.
That's a great ending.
